   {:e #blake3 "1c43750bdfed4ecdc508993f76f071f04900d4d5ff8abc476e38867f6fcc569c" :a :db/ident :v :harvest/session-braid-user-1773953672 :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "1c43750bdfed4ecdc508993f76f071f04900d4d5ff8abc476e38867f6fcc569c" :a :harvest/accomplishments :v "THE SINGLE MOST LEVERAGED ADDITION: Auto-observation from tool calls (zero-cost methodology). Instead of suggesting observations in the footer, auto-transact them as datoms. The contextual_observation_hint() infrastructure already computes text + confidence. Change: hint → display becomes hint → transact + display. ~50 LOC in the footer injection path. Impact: eliminates ceremony-flow tension, feeds CRB with more data, provides session trajectory, reduces M(t) drift, makes harvest threshold less critical. The mathematical reason this works: it changes the cost function c_m from positive (k* tokens consumed) to zero (side effect of existing tool call). When c_m = 0, the temporal discount problem disappears — the agent never has to choose between implement and observe because observe is free.; FIRST-PRINCIPLES ANALYSIS FRAMEWORK — The seven dog-food findings decompose into THREE DEEP THEMES:\n\nTHEME 1: THE CEREMONY-FLOW TENSION (items: harvest noise, skipped observations, session trajectory invisibility)\nAt its core, this is the tension between EXPLICIT KNOWLEDGE CAPTURE (the methodology demands observe → crystallize → task → execute) and IMPLICIT KNOWLEDGE PRODUCTION (the agent produces knowledge continuously as a side-effect of working). The ceremony of explicit capture costs k* tokens and cognitive switching. The radical insight: the methodology should be a FUNCTOR that PRESERVES the agent's natural workflow structure, not a DISTINCT workflow that competes with it.\n\nTHEME 2: THE TITLE-AS-PROMPT PROBLEM (items: task title bloat, schema invisibility)\nEvery task title is a PROMPT that activates the implementer's reasoning. Long titles filled with BACKGROUND/ACCEPTANCE/APPROACH are constraints, not activations. From prompt-optimization: demonstrations > constraints, and the k* threshold means more text often HURTS. The radical insight: the task should be a MULTI-RESOLUTION DOCUMENT with the title as the ACTIVATION SEED (≤25 chars) and the body as the SUPPORTING CONTEXT (available on demand, exactly like ACP).\n\nTHEME 3: THE FOOTER-BODY DUALITY (items: footer/ACP redundancy, guidance-projection gap)\nThe legacy footer and ACP output serve the SAME PURPOSE (tell the agent what to do next) but through DIFFERENT mechanisms (appended text vs structured projection). This duality wastes tokens and creates confusion. The radical insight: the footer IS the output. There should be no distinction between 'the answer' and 'the guidance' — they're the same information projected at different levels. ACP already embodies this insight but the legacy path coexists.\n\nUNIFYING INSIGHT: All three themes are manifestations of ONE underlying problem: BRAID'S OUTPUT IS NOT YET FULLY SELF-SIMILAR. The same information (the action, the context, the methodology state) is represented in different ways at different layers (footer, body, seed, status, task title). Each representation was built independently. ACP started the unification (action-first everywhere). The completion of this unification — where EVERY output surface uses the SAME projection algebra — is the maximally accretive next step.; Session entity: :task/t-ff3fd39d; DEEP DOG-FOOD REFLECTION — Session 027 experience report from the agent's perspective.\n\nWHAT WORKS BRILLIANTLY:\n\n1. braid next IS the killer feature. It told me exactly what to work on at every step. The R(t) routing consistently surfaced the highest-impact task. I never had to guess or scan a list. This is the single most valuable thing braid does — it eliminates the 'what should I work on?' question.\n\n2. braid go / braid task close create a natural work rhythm. Claim → implement → close → next. The ceremony is minimal (one command each) and the store captures the lifecycle. This is better than any external issue tracker because it's IN the conversation — I don't context-switch.\n\n3. braid observe captures insights that would otherwise be lost. The CRB auto-reconciliation is genuinely useful — when I observed the ACP design insight, it surfaced 3+ related spec elements I should check. This prevented me from duplicating existing work.\n\n4. braid task search solved a real pain point. Finding tasks by keyword across 300+ tasks was instant. Before this session, I had to use Datalog queries with keyword matching.\n\n5. The store as append-only truth. Every decision, every task, every observation — it's all in the store. When I needed to check if something was already done, I could query it. This is genuinely different from keeping notes in a file.\n\nWHAT CAUSES FRICTION:\n\n1. THE OUTPUT TRUNCATION (now fixed by ACP). This was the #1 pain point. Before ACP, every braid command was truncated at 50-300 tokens, often cutting off the most important part (the next action). I was working blind — running commands and getting garbled results. ACP fixed this, but the experience of working WITHOUT it for the first hour of the session was genuinely frustrating.\n\n2. Long task titles are still a problem. Even with the L1 title pyramid (≤80 chars), the task descriptions embedded in titles make everything noisy. The root cause: we put EVERYTHING in the title (BACKGROUND, ACCEPTANCE, APPROACH, FILE markers) because there's no good way to view the description field. A 'braid task show' should display the structured sections, but the title IS the description for most tasks.\n\n3. The guidance footer competes with ACP. Now that ACP puts the action first, the legacy footer at the bottom repeats similar information (M(t), next action) but in a different format. This is redundant — the footer should either be suppressed for ACP commands or unified completely.\n\n4. Schema evolution is invisible. I added 8 new schema attributes this session (:task/title-l0, :task/title-l1, :tx/reconciled, 5 :recon-source/* attrs) and got zero feedback. A 'braid schema --new' or a schema diff would help verify the attributes were installed.\n\n5. No way to see my session trajectory. I can see 'last session' in the seed, but I can't see 'what have I done in the CURRENT session?' A 'braid session summary' would help me track progress without harvesting.\n\n6. The harvest threshold is too aggressive. The system warned me about harvest being overdue after 15 transactions. But during a high-velocity implementation session, 15 transactions happen in 5 minutes. The warning became noise — I started ignoring it. The velocity-adaptive threshold (INV-GUIDANCE-019) would fix this but isn't fully wired.\n\nWHAT I WOULD IMPROVE (PRIORITIZED):\n\nP0: Task title/description separation. Create tasks with short titles and put the BACKGROUND/ACCEPTANCE/APPROACH in :task/description. The create CLI should support --body or stdin for the description. This would make every task list 10x more readable.\n\nP1: Session summary command. 'braid session summary' showing: tasks created, tasks closed, observations made, transactions, F(S) delta since session start. Without this, I have to harvest to see my progress.\n\nP1: Unified ACP + footer. The legacy footer should be fully replaced by ACP methodology context blocks for converted commands. Currently they coexist, which is redundant.\n\nP2: Schema diff. 'braid schema --diff' showing attributes added since a given transaction.\n\nP2: Harvest threshold tuning. The 15-tx threshold should adapt to velocity per INV-GUIDANCE-019.\n\nOVERALL ASSESSMENT:\n\nBraid is GENUINELY USEFUL for agentic work. The task management (next → go → close) + observation capture (observe) + session continuity (seed → harvest) form a real workflow that I followed naturally. The ACP innovation is the right architectural direction — action-first output is dramatically better than content-first truncated output.\n\nThe system is at an inflection point: the core abstractions (datom store, task management, guidance routing, bilateral coherence, ACP projection) are all sound and working. The friction points are UX-level issues (title length, schema visibility, footer redundancy) not architectural problems.\n\nThe biggest gap is between what braid CAN do and what the agent ACTUALLY DOES. I followed the methodology (observe → task → execute) most of the time, but under time pressure I skipped observations and went straight to implementation. The system detected this (M(t) dropped) but couldn't prevent it. This is the basin competition problem (ADR-GUIDANCE-002) in action — and it's the hardest problem to solve because it requires the agent to WANT to follow the methodology, not just be reminded to.; THE UNIFYING INSIGHT — FRACTAL SELF-SIMILAR OUTPUT ARCHITECTURE:\n\nEvery information surface in braid should be a PROJECTION of the same underlying ActionProjection algebra. This is self-similarity: the system looks the same at every scale, just at different resolution.\n\nThree implications:\n1. ZERO-COST METHODOLOGY: The tool call IS the observation. Auto-transact observations from tool outputs. Cost of methodology drops to zero.\n2. TASK-AS-ACP: The task IS an ActionProjection. Title = activation seed (≤25 chars). Context = structured sections. Evidence = braid task show.\n3. SINGLE PROJECTION ALGEBRA: Footer = action (no separate rendering). All surfaces are pi(Store, k*, phase, command).\n\nMathematical formulation: natural transformation pi: Store -> Output parameterized by (k*, phase, command).\nProperties: functorial (projections compose), monotone (more budget = more context), action-preserving (action invariant across levels), idempotent (projecting a projection = identity).\n\nThis completes the arc from SEED.md's self-bootstrap principle (C7) to the output layer: the store bootstraps from its own specification, the specification bootstraps from its own data model, and now the output bootstraps from its own projection algebra.; Session entity: :task/t-87510cea; RESEARCH SYNTHESIS — Three agents returned with deep findings that DEEPEN the analysis:\n\nBASIN COMPETITION (Agent 1): Five layers of causal explanation: (1) k* depletion, (2) self-reinforcing trajectory (agent's own outputs demonstrate Basin B), (3) asymmetric friction (Basin B has zero activation energy), (4) manifold deformation (Basin A attractor disappears as context grows), (5) information-theoretic: finite signal vs constant bias — outcome predetermined. The RADICAL solution from transcript 05: 'Don't make Basin A stronger — make Basin B structurally unavailable.' If the datom store is the ONLY interface to project state, skipping DDIS becomes incoherent. Direction 3 (spec-language = code-language, no basin distinction) is the most promising near-term path.\n\nTASK TITLE BLOAT (Agent 2): Average task title is 200+ chars (~50 tokens). Propagates to 7 downstream locations (R(t) label, seed intention, DMP, task show). Root cause: positional CLI arg is lowest friction. The TASK-DECOMPOSE logic already parses BACKGROUND/ACCEPTANCE/FILE sections from titles. Solution: structured document via stdin (braid task create - <<EOF), title capped at 120 chars, promoted sections as first-class schema attributes. This makes the title pyramid UNNECESSARY — 120-char titles don't need L0/L1 compression.\n\nHARVEST LIFECYCLE (Agent 3): The spec (INV-GUIDANCE-019) defines a richer harvest_urgency formula than implemented: max(tx_since/threshold, minutes_since/30, high_value_unharvested/3, k_eff_critical). Only the first signal is wired. Auto-transact COF hints as low-confidence exploration datoms is the bridge: ~50 LOC change eliminates the ceremony-flow tension. Harvest becomes 'review and promote' not 'detect and capture'. Session summary should compose synthesize_narrative() + compute_routing() for live trajectory view.; Session entity: :task/t-3b6c89e7\nSession entity: :task/t-e2e64fe4; Session entity: :task/t-bd702d60; Session entity: :task/t-2e81e43a; Session entity: :task/t-5f7d113a; Session entity: :task/t-9800d190; Session entity: :task/t-0ee28424; Session entity: :task/t-ca43c759; Session entity: :task/t-d38d4c45; Session entity: :task/t-51301c92; Session entity: :task/t-46762ee9; Session entity: :task/t-a79f7345" :op :assert}
